</div>
<div style="background-color: #f2edd7; padding: 64px 40px;">
    <div style="max-width: 860px; margin: 0 auto;">
        <div style="display: flex; align-items: center; gap: 20px; margin-bottom: 32px; flex-wrap: wrap;">
            <div style="background-color: #cba258; border-radius: 50%; width: 62px; height: 62px; display: flex; align-items: center; justify-content: center; flex-shrink: 0;"><span style="font-family: 'Playfair Display', serif; font-size: 26px; color: #1e3932;">2</span></div>
            <div>
                <p style="font-family: 'Lato', sans-serif; font-size: 11px; color: #1e3932; margin: 0 0 4px 0;">Day Two</p>
                <h2 style="font-family: 'Playfair Display', serif; font-size: 30px; color: #1e3932; margin: 0;">History, Questions, and Your Direction</h2>
            </div>
        </div>
        <p style="font-family: 'Lato', sans-serif; font-size: 16px; color: #333; line-height: 1.85; margin: 0 0 30px 0;">Today has two major goals: understanding the historical arc of voting barriers in North Carolina, and locking in your research question before I leave for two days. You need to be ready to go by the end of class. This is the day that sets everything in motion.</p>
        <div style="background-color: #ffffff; border-radius: 10px; padding: 28px 32px; margin-bottom: 22px;">
            <h3 style="font-family: 'Playfair Display', serif; font-size: 20px; color: #1e3932; margin: 0 0 6px 0;">Part 1: A 15-Minute Historical Overview</h3>
            <p style="font-family: 'Lato', sans-serif; font-size: 15px; color: #333; line-height: 1.8; margin: 0 0 18px 0;">We are going to <a class="inline_disabled" href="https://docs.google.com/document/d/1r_NmmnWi42BbbDOp0Sk5igJRw2sRgXmqUAj04OedIwo/edit?tab=t.0" target="_blank" rel="noopener">trace voting rights</a> in North Carolina from 1776 to today. The goal is not to memorize every date. The goal is to see how barriers evolved from explicit and written into law to systemic and harder to see, and how some are being added back in right now.</p>
            <div style="border-left: 3px solid #CBA258; padding-left: 22px; display: flex; flex-direction: column; gap: 16px;">
                <div>
                    <p style="font-family: 'Lato', sans-serif; font-size: 14px; color: #1e3932; margin: 0 0 4px 0;">1776: North Carolina Constitution</p>
                    <p style="font-family: 'Lato', sans-serif; font-size: 14px; color: #555; margin: 0; line-height: 1.7;">Who was allowed to vote from the beginning? Who was already left out before the country was even established?</p>
                </div>
                <div>
                    <p style="font-family: 'Lato', sans-serif; font-size: 14px; color: #1e3932; margin: 0 0 4px 0;">1835: The Language Shifts</p>
                    <p style="font-family: 'Lato', sans-serif; font-size: 14px; color: #555; margin: 0; line-height: 1.7;">The constitution was rewritten. We'll look at the debate between Morehead and Schubert at the convention: one wanted to bar Black voters from both chambers, one was willing to allow property-owning Black men into one. What does that conflict reveal about how barriers get built?</p>
                </div>
                <div>
                    <p style="font-family: 'Lato', sans-serif; font-size: 14px; color: #1e3932; margin: 0 0 4px 0;">Post-Civil War and Reconstruction</p>
                    <p style="font-family: 'Lato', sans-serif; font-size: 14px; color: #555; margin: 0; line-height: 1.7;">The 15th Amendment requires that Black men be allowed to vote. How did states respond? What new barriers appeared even when the law said they couldn't exist?</p>
                </div>
                <div>
                    <p style="font-family: 'Lato', sans-serif; font-size: 14px; color: #1e3932; margin: 0 0 4px 0;">Jim Crow Era: Literacy Tests and Poll Taxes</p>
                    <p style="font-family: 'Lato', sans-serif; font-size: 14px; color: #555; margin: 0; line-height: 1.7;">Legal barriers were replaced with procedural ones. Literacy tests, poll taxes, and intimidation were used to keep people from exercising a right the law said they had.</p>
                </div>
                <div>
                    <p style="font-family: 'Lato', sans-serif; font-size: 14px; color: #1e3932; margin: 0 0 4px 0;">19th Amendment: Women Gain the Right to Vote</p>
                    <p style="font-family: 'Lato', sans-serif; font-size: 14px; color: #555; margin: 0; line-height: 1.7;">Women are included, but literacy tests are still in use. Access and rights are not the same thing.</p>
                </div>
                <div style="background-color: #f2edd7; border-radius: 8px; padding: 18px 22px;">
                    <p style="font-family: 'Lato', sans-serif; font-size: 14px; color: #1e3932; margin: 0 0 6px 0;">1971: The North Carolina Constitution in Use Today</p>
                    <p style="font-family: 'Lato', sans-serif; font-size: 14px; color: #555; margin: 0 0 10px 0; line-height: 1.7;">Article VI, Section 4 still contains this language: every person presenting themselves for voter registration must be able to read and write any section of the Constitution in the English language. It is unenforceable under federal law. But it is still there. What does it mean that we haven't removed it?</p>
                    <p style="font-family: 'Lato', sans-serif; font-size: 14px; color: #1e3932; font-style: italic; margin: 0; line-height: 1.7;">Explicit barriers have been legally dismantled. But systemic ones persist, and new ones are being debated right now. That is your bridge into your own research.</p>
                </div>
            </div>
        </div>
        <div style="background-color: #ffffff; border-radius: 10px; padding: 28px 32px; margin-bottom: 22px;">
            <h3 style="font-family: 'Playfair Display', serif; font-size: 20px; color: #1e3932; margin: 0 0 16px 0;">Part 2: Developing Your Research Question</h3>
            <p style="font-family: 'Lato', sans-serif; font-size: 15px; color: #333; line-height: 1.8; margin: 0 0 18px 0;">Your research question is the engine of everything that happens next. Here is what makes a strong one for this lesson:</p>
            <div style="display: flex; flex-direction: column; gap: 12px; margin-bottom: 22px;">
                <div style="display: flex; gap: 12px; align-items: flex-start;"><span style="color: #cba258; font-size: 17px; flex-shrink: 0; line-height: 1.6;">✓</span>
                    <p style="font-family: 'Lato', sans-serif; font-size: 15px; color: #333; margin: 0; line-height: 1.7;"><strong>Open-ended and researchable</strong> -- not something you can look up and answer in two minutes</p>
                </div>
                <div style="display: flex; gap: 12px; align-items: flex-start;"><span style="color: #cba258; font-size: 17px; flex-shrink: 0; line-height: 1.6;">✓</span>
                    <p style="font-family: 'Lato', sans-serif; font-size: 15px; color: #333; margin: 0; line-height: 1.7;"><strong>Costa's Level 2 or 3</strong> -- you are analyzing, evaluating, or synthesizing, not just recalling a fact</p>
                </div>
                <div style="display: flex; gap: 12px; align-items: flex-start;"><span style="color: #cba258; font-size: 17px; flex-shrink: 0; line-height: 1.6;">✓</span>
                    <p style="font-family: 'Lato', sans-serif; font-size: 15px; color: #333; margin: 0; line-height: 1.7;"><strong>Focused on voting barriers</strong> -- it stays within the scope of our essential question</p>
                </div>
                <div style="display: flex; gap: 12px; align-items: flex-start;"><span style="color: #cba258; font-size: 17px; flex-shrink: 0; line-height: 1.6;">✓</span>
                    <p style="font-family: 'Lato', sans-serif; font-size: 15px; color: #333; margin: 0; line-height: 1.7;"><strong>Specific to a demographic or situation</strong> -- young voters, rural communities, non-English speakers, citizenship requirements, polling site access, etc.</p>
                </div>
                <div style="display: flex; gap: 12px; align-items: flex-start;"><span style="color: #cba258; font-size: 17px; flex-shrink: 0; line-height: 1.6;">✓</span>
                    <p style="font-family: 'Lato', sans-serif; font-size: 15px; color: #333; margin: 0; line-height: 1.7;"><strong>Pushes toward possibility</strong> -- ideally explores both the barrier and whether we as a society want to address it or keep it</p>
                </div>
            </div>
            <div style="background-color: #f2edd7; border-radius: 8px; padding: 20px 24px; margin-bottom: 18px;">
                <p style="font-family: 'Lato', sans-serif; font-size: 12px; color: #1e3932; margin: 0 0 12px 0;">Example Questions</p>
                <p style="font-family: 'Lato', sans-serif; font-size: 14px; color: #333; line-height: 1.8; margin: 0 0 10px 0; font-style: italic;">"Why do young people in North Carolina vote at lower rates than older voters, and what would actually make them show up to the polls?"</p>
                <p style="font-family: 'Lato', sans-serif; font-size: 14px; color: #333; line-height: 1.8; margin: 0 0 10px 0; font-style: italic;">"How do work schedules and transportation keep rural voters from participating, and is this a barrier our society wants to fix?"</p>
                <p style="font-family: 'Lato', sans-serif; font-size: 14px; color: #333; line-height: 1.8; margin: 0; font-style: italic;">What about the new federal requirements that are being presented?&nbsp; Are they necessary? What about other demographics?&nbsp; What about voter ID requirements in NC?&nbsp; Mail-in ballots?</p>
            </div>
            <p style="font-family: 'Lato', sans-serif; font-size: 14px; color: #555; line-height: 1.75; margin: 0;">You may work independently or with one partner. No groups larger than two.</p>
        </div>
        <div style="background-color: #ffffff; border-radius: 10px; padding: 28px 32px; margin-bottom: 22px;">
            <h3 style="font-family: 'Playfair Display', serif; font-size: 20px; color: #1e3932; margin: 0 0 16px 0;">Part 3: Peer Feedback on Your Question</h3>
            <p style="font-family: 'Lato', sans-serif; font-size: 15px; color: #333; line-height: 1.8; margin: 0 0 18px 0;">Once you've drafted your research question, you'll share it with your table. Your peers will use the criteria above to respond. When you receive feedback, you have three options:</p>
            <div style="display: flex; flex-wrap: wrap; gap: 14px; margin-bottom: 0;">
                <div style="background-color: #1e3932; border-radius: 8px; padding: 18px 20px; flex: 1; min-width: 150px;">
                    <p style="font-family: 'Lato', sans-serif; font-size: 11px; color: #cba258; margin: 0 0 6px 0;">Act On It</p>
                    <p style="font-family: 'Lato', sans-serif; font-size: 14px; color: #f2edd7; margin: 0; line-height: 1.65;">This feedback makes your question stronger. You're going to change it.</p>
                </div>
                <div style="background-color: #1e3932; border-radius: 8px; padding: 18px 20px; flex: 1; min-width: 150px;">
                    <p style="font-family: 'Lato', sans-serif; font-size: 11px; color: #cba258; margin: 0 0 6px 0;">Reflect On It</p>
                    <p style="font-family: 'Lato', sans-serif; font-size: 14px; color: #f2edd7; margin: 0; line-height: 1.65;">Interesting, but not where you're headed right now. You'll note it and move on.</p>
                </div>
                <div style="background-color: #1e3932; border-radius: 8px; padding: 18px 20px; flex: 1; min-width: 150px;">
                    <p style="font-family: 'Lato', sans-serif; font-size: 11px; color: #cba258; margin: 0 0 6px 0;">Ignore It</p>
                    <p style="font-family: 'Lato', sans-serif; font-size: 14px; color: #f2edd7; margin: 0; line-height: 1.65;">It doesn't align with what you're trying to do. You're the researcher here.</p>
                </div>
            </div>
        </div>
        <div style="background-color: #1e3932; border-radius: 10px; padding: 28px 32px;">
            <h3 style="font-family: 'Playfair Display', serif; font-size: 20px; color: #f2edd7; margin: 0 0 14px 0;">Part 4: One-on-One with Mr. Fussell</h3>
            <p style="font-family: 'Lato', sans-serif; font-size: 15px; color: #d4e9e2; line-height: 1.8; margin: 0 0 14px 0;">Before class ends today, I will meet briefly with each individual or partnership. Come ready with your research question and a clear sense of what types of information you are going to need to answer it. You don't need to have your actual articles or sources yet. But you need to know what you're looking for: data, scholarly research, opinion-based sources, or a combination.</p>
            <p style="font-family: 'Lato', sans-serif; font-size: 15px; color: #d4e9e2; line-height: 1.8; margin: 0;">I'll confirm your question, push back if needed, or help you sharpen your direction. You leave today knowing exactly where you're going. Then you're on your own for two days.</p>
        </div>
    </div>
</div>
<div style="background-color: #1e3932; padding: 64px 40px;">
    <div style="max-width: 860px; margin: 0 auto;">
        <div style="display: flex; align-items: center; gap: 20px; margin-bottom: 32px; flex-wrap: wrap;">
            <div style="background-color: #f2edd7; border-radius: 50%; width: 62px; height: 62px; display: flex; align-items: center; justify-content: center; flex-shrink: 0;"><span style="font-family: 'Playfair Display', serif; font-size: 20px; color: #1e3932;">3-4</span></div>
            <div>
                <p style="font-family: 'Lato', sans-serif; font-size: 11px; color: #cba258; margin: 0 0 4px 0;">Days Three and Four</p>
                <h2 style="font-family: 'Playfair Display', serif; font-size: 30px; color: #f2edd7; margin: 0;">This Is Your Time. Do the Work.</h2>
            </div>
        </div>
        <div style="background-color: rgba(255,255,255,0.07); border-radius: 10px; padding: 28px 32px; margin-bottom: 22px;">
            <p style="font-family: 'Lato', sans-serif; font-size: 16px; color: #f2edd7; line-height: 1.85; margin: 0 0 14px 0;">I am not in the classroom these two days. That means this time belongs entirely to you. You have your research question. You know what types of sources you need. Now go find them and figure out what you actually believe.</p>
            <p style="font-family: 'Lato', sans-serif; font-size: 16px; color: #d4e9e2; line-height: 1.85; margin: 0;">You have done independent research before, in this class, with Jester, and in other places. You know how to operate. Here is what is expected across these two days.</p>
        </div>
        <div style="display: flex; flex-wrap: wrap; gap: 18px; margin-bottom: 22px;">
            <div style="background-color: rgba(255,255,255,0.07); border-radius: 10px; padding: 24px 28px; flex: 1; min-width: 240px;">
                <p style="font-family: 'Lato', sans-serif; font-size: 11px; color: #cba258; margin: 0 0 12px 0;">Day 3: Research</p>
                <p style="font-family: 'Lato', sans-serif; font-size: 15px; color: #d4e9e2; line-height: 1.8; margin: 0;">Dig into your question. Find real sources. You are looking for a mix of scholarly or expert research on your barrier, data that shows the scope of the problem, and opinion-based articles that reveal how people disagree about whether and how to address it.</p>
            </div>
            <div style="background-color: rgba(255,255,255,0.07); border-radius: 10px; padding: 24px 28px; flex: 1; min-width: 240px;">
                <p style="font-family: 'Lato', sans-serif; font-size: 11px; color: #cba258; margin: 0 0 12px 0;">Day 4: Synthesize and Build</p>
                <p style="font-family: 'Lato', sans-serif; font-size: 15px; color: #d4e9e2; line-height: 1.8; margin: 0;">Take what you have found and start building your presentation artifact. What does the research show? What do you believe based on the evidence? Start shaping your argument and building whatever you are going to present. You should have a clear direction by end of today.</p>
            </div>
        </div>
        <div style="background-color: #cba258; border-radius: 10px; padding: 24px 30px;">
            <p style="font-family: 'Lato', sans-serif; font-size: 12px; color: #1e3932; margin: 0 0 8px 0;">Important</p>
            <p style="font-family: 'Lato', sans-serif; font-size: 15px; color: #1e3932; line-height: 1.8; margin: 0;">You are allowed to argue in any direction your research takes you. If the evidence shows that a particular barrier is a necessary protection for election integrity, argue that and back it up. If the evidence shows it is unnecessarily disenfranchising legal voters, argue that and back it up. What is not acceptable is an opinion without data and research behind it.</p>
        </div>
    </div>
</div>
<div style="background-color: #ffffff; padding: 64px 40px;">
    <div style="max-width: 860px; margin: 0 auto;">
        <div style="display: flex; align-items: center; gap: 20px; margin-bottom: 32px; flex-wrap: wrap;">
            <div style="background-color: #1e3932; border-radius: 50%; width: 62px; height: 62px; display: flex; align-items: center; justify-content: center; flex-shrink: 0;"><span style="font-family: 'Playfair Display', serif; font-size: 26px; color: #cba258;">5</span></div>
            <div>
                <p style="font-family: 'Lato', sans-serif; font-size: 11px; color: #cba258; margin: 0 0 4px 0;">Day Five</p>
                <h2 style="font-family: 'Playfair Display', serif; font-size: 30px; color: #1e3932; margin: 0;">Mr. Fussell Is Back. Let's Get You Ready.</h2>
            </div>
        </div>
        <p style="font-family: 'Lato', sans-serif; font-size: 16px; color: #333; line-height: 1.85; margin: 0 0 30px 0;">Today is entirely about making sure every single person is ready to present. I will spend the full class period meeting with every individual and partnership. We are not starting anything new today. We are finishing what you started.</p>
        <div style="background-color: #f2edd7; border-radius: 10px; padding: 28px 32px; margin-bottom: 22px;">
            <h3 style="font-family: 'Playfair Display', serif; font-size: 20px; color: #1e3932; margin: 0 0 18px 0;">Come Ready to Show Me</h3>
            <div style="display: flex; flex-direction: column; gap: 12px;">
                <div style="display: flex; gap: 12px; align-items: flex-start;"><span style="color: #cba258; font-size: 16px; flex-shrink: 0; line-height: 1.7;">&rarr;</span>
                    <p style="font-family: 'Lato', sans-serif; font-size: 15px; color: #333; margin: 0; line-height: 1.7;">Your finalized research question</p>
                </div>
                <div style="display: flex; gap: 12px; align-items: flex-start;"><span style="color: #cba258; font-size: 16px; flex-shrink: 0; line-height: 1.7;">&rarr;</span>
                    <p style="font-family: 'Lato', sans-serif; font-size: 15px; color: #333; margin: 0; line-height: 1.7;">Your sources: scholarly or expert research, data, and at least one opinion-based piece</p>
                </div>
                <div style="display: flex; gap: 12px; align-items: flex-start;"><span style="color: #cba258; font-size: 16px; flex-shrink: 0; line-height: 1.7;">&rarr;</span>
                    <p style="font-family: 'Lato', sans-serif; font-size: 15px; color: #333; margin: 0; line-height: 1.7;">Your artifact in progress or complete</p>
                </div>
                <div style="display: flex; gap: 12px; align-items: flex-start;"><span style="color: #cba258; font-size: 16px; flex-shrink: 0; line-height: 1.7;">&rarr;</span>
                    <p style="font-family: 'Lato', sans-serif; font-size: 15px; color: #333; margin: 0; line-height: 1.7;">Your argument: what do you believe based on what you found, and can you back it up?</p>
                </div>
            </div>
        </div>
        <div style="background-color: #1e3932; border-radius: 10px; padding: 24px 30px;">
            <p style="font-family: 'Lato', sans-serif; font-size: 15px; color: #d4e9e2; line-height: 1.8; margin: 0;">If you still have things to polish after today, you have the weekend. Presentations begin Monday. The order is completely random. You will find out the day of who goes when. Be ready to present from the very start of Day 6.</p>
